        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Ashton Lodge, | Bassett, Southampton.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Friday</date>
                    <salute>My dear Father</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Please ask Mother to decipher the enclosed from Capt Forrest chief Constable of Hants.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I know Knight<ref target="#foot.f3"/> a little he seems above the average in brains, &amp; I would sooner take Capt Forrest’s opinion as to his fitness than any man I know.</p>
<p>I suppose you could hardly send it to Sir John as he is called a “Beak”<ref target="#foot.f4"/> but if he calls perhaps you could mention his name, as I should like to oblige Forrest. I have told him you will have nothing to do with the election, or Sir J. either probably.</p>
<p>I am afraid you know no one well enough at Maidstone<ref target="#foot.f5"/> to enclose the note to without comment. If as good as any other Knight deserves a lift as he has been shamefully cut out by his Father for a marriage (to a very pleasant person)</p>
<p>I did not see Hacon,<ref target="#foot.f6"/> but told the case to his head man, &amp; expect a letter.</p>
<p>Your affect son | W E. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The date range is based on the address. William lived at Ashton Lodge from around 1869 until 1875.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">The enclosure from <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1690.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">John Henry Forrest</ref>, chief constable of Hampshire, has not been found.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Knight has not been identified.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3026.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">John Lubbock</ref> was justice of the peace for Kent (<hi rend="italic">Burke’s peerage</hi>). ‘Beak’ is slang for magistrate or justice of the peace (<hi rend="italic">OED</hi>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">Lubbock was Liberal MP for Maidstone, Kent, from 1870 to 1880 (<hi rend="italic">ODNB</hi>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f6"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2042.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">William Mackmurdo Hacon</ref> was CD’s solicitor.</note>
        </div>        
            
